00:10:37.390 --> 00:10:40.300
So notional makes
something really big

00:10:40.300 --> 00:10:42.550
seem bigger than it is.

00:10:42.550 --> 00:10:47.880
But a lot of the
derivatives that are here,

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:49.450
there's another
derivative in there

00:10:49.450 --> 00:10:51.640
that is the offsetting bet.

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:54.430
So this is not a one-way
bet that everyone is

00:10:54.430 --> 00:10:56.380
making on one particular thing.

00:10:56.380 --> 00:10:59.740
This is millions and millions of
things with insurance companies

00:10:59.740 --> 00:11:05.080
hedging and investment people
playing both sides and banks

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:06.640
betting on both sides.

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:10.750
So it's probably less scary than
the amount of boxes implies.

00:11:10.750 --> 00:11:12.820
SPEAKER: I look at this
as almost the sportsbook

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:14.050
at the casino, is that right?

00:11:14.050 --> 00:11:15.592
It's like I'm betting
that the game--

00:11:15.592 --> 00:11:16.591
JOSH BROWN: That's fair.

00:11:16.591 --> 00:11:17.440
SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:20.110
JOSH BROWN: So
probably, the casino--

00:11:20.110 --> 00:11:21.670
only for a portion
of the people that

00:11:21.670 --> 00:11:22.879
are playing in these markets.

00:11:22.879 --> 00:11:25.128
A lot of the people that are
playing in these markets,

00:11:25.128 --> 00:11:27.030
you think about a
company like Cargill.

00:11:27.030 --> 00:11:28.801
It's an agricultural company.

00:11:28.801 --> 00:11:29.800
They have a lot of risk.

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:33.460
If it's a bumper crop,
prices will drop.

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:36.250
If there's terrible weather,
there won't be enough supply.

00:11:36.250 --> 00:11:39.310
And they've got to use
commodity markets to hedge

00:11:39.310 --> 00:11:40.295
what their exposure is.

00:11:40.295 --> 00:11:42.670
You think about a bank doing
business all over the world,

00:11:42.670 --> 00:11:46.030
like Citigroup, they've
got currency exposure.

00:11:46.030 --> 00:11:48.380
They have corporate
clients all over the world.

00:11:48.380 --> 00:11:50.320
So a lot of this stuff
is really companies

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:53.970
offloading risk, rather than
trying to take more risk.

00:11:53.970 --> 00:11:55.900
And then there are
speculators in the market.

00:11:55.900 --> 00:12:01.290
So maybe the casino aspect of
it is not quite as pronounced.

00:12:01.290 --> 00:12:03.720
The one thing the media has
done with the term derivatives

00:12:03.720 --> 00:12:05.940
is they've added a
connotation to it.

00:12:05.940 --> 00:12:06.960
It's kind of a loaded--

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:08.472
ooh, derivatives.

00:12:08.472 --> 00:12:09.180
That's code for--

00:12:09.180 --> 00:12:09.990
SPEAKER: They took us down.

00:12:09.990 --> 00:12:12.115
JOSH BROWN: That's code
for, I don't understand it,

00:12:12.115 --> 00:12:15.870
so it must be bad,
or these somehow

00:12:15.870 --> 00:12:17.370
represent speculative bets.

00:12:17.370 --> 00:12:22.554
When in reality, a lot of it is
attempting to minimize risks.

00:12:22.554 --> 00:12:23.220
SPEAKER: Got it.

