Hopefully that was
eye-opening for some people.

00:12:32.260 --> 00:12:38.035
I'm going to move
on, now, to you.

00:12:38.035 --> 00:12:43.010
OK, I hope this isn't too
personal of a question,

00:12:43.010 --> 00:12:47.780
but what dark past or
VH1 "Behind the Music"

00:12:47.780 --> 00:12:51.490
story leads to you becoming
the reformed broker?

00:12:51.490 --> 00:12:52.820
What's reformed?

00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:56.100
JOSH BROWN: Yeah, so I
did the book about it in--

00:12:56.100 --> 00:13:01.190
I wrote it in 2011, which
was about a year post leaving

00:13:01.190 --> 00:13:02.540
the brokerage industry.

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:06.080
But long story short, I come
from this really strange place

00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:08.210
on the east coast
called Long Island.

00:13:08.210 --> 00:13:13.910
And in the mid-to-late-1990s,
every aggressive young male got

00:13:13.910 --> 00:13:15.560
a Series 7 and became a broker.

00:13:15.560 --> 00:13:18.350
It's just what you did.

00:13:18.350 --> 00:13:21.740
If you grew up in Nebraska,
you became a football player

00:13:21.740 --> 00:13:24.080
and you were a Cornhusker.

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:27.500
So for whatever reason, what we
did was we became stockbrokers.

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:30.470
And it was the golden age
of being a stockbroker,

00:13:30.470 --> 00:13:32.210
because it was pre-internet.

00:13:32.210 --> 00:13:36.020
It was pre-people having
access to building

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:37.370
their own portfolio.

00:13:37.370 --> 00:13:38.930
Charles Schwab was out there.

00:13:38.930 --> 00:13:42.440
Used to call Charles Schwab,
and you would pay like $10

00:13:42.440 --> 00:13:45.020
to get 15 stock quotes
read to you over the phone.

00:13:45.020 --> 00:13:46.550
It's a true story.

00:13:46.550 --> 00:13:48.230
So people wanted
access to the market,

00:13:48.230 --> 00:13:49.938
and the only way they
could really get it

00:13:49.938 --> 00:13:51.140
was via a stockbroker.

00:13:51.140 --> 00:13:54.470
So there was some glamor
to being a broker,

00:13:54.470 --> 00:13:56.960
and there were high-end
versions and low-end versions.

00:13:56.960 --> 00:14:02.270
And I was screwing
around in college.

00:14:02.270 --> 00:14:06.230
Didn't really have any serious
passion to do anything.

00:14:06.230 --> 00:14:09.530
And my dad said, you should talk
to my friend from the country

00:14:09.530 --> 00:14:10.760
club that I play golf with.

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:12.950
I think he makes a
million dollars a day.

00:14:12.950 --> 00:14:15.080
Go get a job with him.

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:17.030
My dad, he doesn't
know anything.

00:14:17.030 --> 00:14:18.350
So I meet the guy.

00:14:18.350 --> 00:14:20.180
He hires me 15
minutes later, which

00:14:20.180 --> 00:14:22.470
should have been a red flag.

00:14:22.470 --> 00:14:25.460
But I am studying
for a Series 7, which

00:14:25.460 --> 00:14:28.370
is a very low barrier to entry.

00:14:28.370 --> 00:14:31.970
You need like a 60 IQ
to pass the tests--

00:14:31.970 --> 00:14:33.630
also should have
been a red flag.

00:14:33.630 --> 00:14:35.300
But I passed it.

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:36.800
They handed me a
telephone, and they

00:14:36.800 --> 00:14:41.730
said, call these 500
people today, and I did.

00:14:41.730 --> 00:14:44.270
And out of the 500 people,
50 people would talk to you.

00:14:44.270 --> 00:14:46.430
Out of those 50 people, 10
of them would have money

00:14:46.430 --> 00:14:48.530
and would be interested
in hearing from you again.

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:51.113
You would call those people back
a week later after you mailed

00:14:51.113 --> 00:14:53.250
them a brochure that
had a sailboat on it,

00:14:53.250 --> 00:14:57.950
and you would sell
them Callaway Golf IPO.

00:14:57.950 --> 00:14:59.990
Snapple is coming public.

00:14:59.990 --> 00:15:02.205
This is like '96, '97.

00:15:02.205 --> 00:15:04.430
So I was a cold caller.

00:15:04.430 --> 00:15:07.790
Not able to sell stocks, but
introducing a senior broker.

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:10.550
My senior broker
had five Porsches,

00:15:10.550 --> 00:15:12.630
one for each day of the week.

00:15:12.630 --> 00:15:17.010
And prior to being a
broker, he was a bouncer.

00:15:17.010 --> 00:15:21.740
I mean, when you're 20 or
21, you're like, all right,

00:15:21.740 --> 00:15:22.830
this is amazing.

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:24.320
Everyone's getting rich.

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:26.614
The market keeps going up.

00:15:26.614 --> 00:15:28.280
And there were all
these IPOs, and we're

00:15:28.280 --> 00:15:31.560
getting pieces of them and
we're helping people invest.

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:33.930
And so I probably was
really, really good at it.

00:15:33.930 --> 00:15:36.420
So nobody quits something
they're good at, right?

00:15:36.420 --> 00:15:38.522
If you're good at something,
you keep doing it.

00:15:38.522 --> 00:15:40.730
And all the nagging thoughts
in the back of my head--

00:15:40.730 --> 00:15:43.980
am I qualified to be telling
people how to invest?

00:15:43.980 --> 00:15:47.130
I don't think I am, but
they're listening to me.

00:15:47.130 --> 00:15:51.230
So I did it, and then
the financial crisis

00:15:51.230 --> 00:15:53.500
was a wake-up call,
because everything I

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:55.670
had done for people--
and I did my best.

00:15:55.670 --> 00:15:58.521
Sell them the right stock,
mutual fund, whatever.

00:15:58.521 --> 00:16:00.020
But then you realize--
you look back

00:16:00.020 --> 00:16:02.390
and you said, all
I really did was

00:16:02.390 --> 00:16:06.950
sell people investments when I
should have been advising them.

00:16:06.950 --> 00:16:08.340
So that was a
great wake-up call.

00:16:08.340 --> 00:16:10.640
And I met my partner,
Barry Ritholtz,

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:14.300
because he was the
guy writing the blogs.

00:16:14.300 --> 00:16:17.210
He started when you were
posting on GeoCities,

00:16:17.210 --> 00:16:19.040
back when you would
write for 30 minutes

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:23.240
and then code for 30 minutes
to get it published-- '98, '99.

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:25.740
But I met Barry, and Barry
was telling the truth.

00:16:25.740 --> 00:16:27.770
And I said, I could
totally do that.

00:16:27.770 --> 00:16:31.116
So I started the
blog 10 years ago.

00:16:31.116 --> 00:16:32.740
Millions and millions
of readers later,

00:16:32.740 --> 00:16:35.540
I'm still doing it
pretty much every day,

00:16:35.540 --> 00:16:37.670
although not while I'm out here.

00:16:37.670 --> 00:16:41.270
But on a daily basis,
I'm putting stuff out.

00:16:41.270 --> 00:16:44.720
And I'm like the worst nightmare
for traditional Wall Street,

00:16:44.720 --> 00:16:46.760
because I know where all
the bodies are buried,

00:16:46.760 --> 00:16:49.580
and I've spent much
of the last 10 years--

00:16:49.580 --> 00:16:54.500
almost daily-- talking about the
ways in which traditional stock

00:16:54.500 --> 00:16:56.600
brokerage, hedge
fund, et cetera--

00:16:56.600 --> 00:16:59.030
all the pitfalls, all
the ways that people

00:16:59.030 --> 00:17:00.320
spend more than they should.

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:01.070
People lose money.

00:17:01.070 --> 00:17:02.210
People are tricked.

00:17:02.210 --> 00:17:04.970
People are misdirected into
investments that are not

00:17:04.970 --> 00:17:06.260
in their best interests.

00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:09.890
And I haven't made a lot of
friends south of 14th street

00:17:09.890 --> 00:17:11.810
in New York, but all
over the country,

00:17:11.810 --> 00:17:15.079
people get what I'm saying
and they agree with it.

00:17:15.079 --> 00:17:19.130
And their enthusiasm for the
truths that I've been telling

00:17:19.130 --> 00:17:22.619
have kept me at it.

00:17:22.619 --> 00:17:25.560
And now I've broken into the
mainstream financial media,

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:27.980
which is an even worse
nightmare, because all

00:17:27.980 --> 00:17:32.480
the advertisers are companies
that I'm then saying,

00:17:32.480 --> 00:17:34.430
no, you don't really need that.

00:17:34.430 --> 00:17:37.467
But they keep booking
me, so I keep doing it.

00:17:37.467 --> 00:17:39.050
SPEAKER: Well, I
definitely appreciate

00:17:39.050 --> 00:17:41.100
the candor you bring to
the "Halftime Report."

00:17:41.100 --> 00:17:41.610
JOSH BROWN: Thank you.

00:17:41.610 --> 00:17:43.609
SPEAKER: It's an awesome
show-- everyone on it--

00:17:43.609 --> 00:17:45.900
and I love what you do there.

