to do as little trading

00:32:52.450 --> 00:32:54.820
as possible so as
not to get whipsawed.

00:32:54.820 --> 00:32:57.777
And in a defined downtrend--
and not a downtrend

00:32:57.777 --> 00:32:59.860
where I'm like, hey, that
looks like a downtrend--

00:32:59.860 --> 00:33:04.210
but mathematically defined by
the slope of what the index is

00:33:04.210 --> 00:33:07.570
doing on a monthly,
moving average basis,

00:33:07.570 --> 00:33:09.400
we want to have less exposure.

00:33:09.400 --> 00:33:13.240
Even if that means there
is this cataclysmic event

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:15.070
and then the market
rebounds and we're

00:33:15.070 --> 00:33:19.540
forced to buy back and hire
as a new uptrend, that's fine.

00:33:19.540 --> 00:33:21.130
We look at it as insurance.

00:33:21.130 --> 00:33:23.650
It's not an alpha strategy,
what we're doing tactically.

00:33:23.650 --> 00:33:27.370
But by marrying strategic,
long-term investing with

00:33:27.370 --> 00:33:29.230
a tactical piece--

00:33:29.230 --> 00:33:31.230
I talked all about
investor behavior.

00:33:31.230 --> 00:33:32.200
It's not lip service.

00:33:32.200 --> 00:33:33.870
It's literally--
what we do is manage

00:33:33.870 --> 00:33:35.600
the psychology of investors.

00:33:35.600 --> 00:33:39.160
So if what we need to do is
limit how much equity exposure

00:33:39.160 --> 00:33:45.140
they have in a bear market,
it's OK if Jack Bogle disagrees.

00:33:45.140 --> 00:33:47.240
I have to face investors.

00:33:47.240 --> 00:33:48.230
He doesn't.

00:33:48.230 --> 00:33:52.610
So it's nice to have a
grandiloquent, overarching

00:33:52.610 --> 00:33:54.110
philosophy of never do anything.

00:33:54.110 --> 00:33:56.060
Just buy and close your eyes.

00:33:56.060 --> 00:33:57.950
But I'm in the
business 20 years.

00:33:57.950 --> 00:33:59.370
I know that's not real.

00:33:59.370 --> 00:34:04.640
So I think we've married the
two approaches that we just saw.

00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:07.460
We just saw the Nobel
Prize for economics awarded

00:34:07.460 --> 00:34:08.929
to-- for the first time ever--

00:34:08.929 --> 00:34:10.670
three economists at once.

00:34:10.670 --> 00:34:14.540
I forget the third guy, but
importantly, Bob Shiller--

00:34:14.540 --> 00:34:15.409
he wins.

00:34:15.409 --> 00:34:20.239
His theory's about bubbles
and cycles driven by emotion.

00:34:20.239 --> 00:34:22.940
He wins at the same time
as Gene Fama, who says,

00:34:22.940 --> 00:34:25.310
there are no bubbles,
and markets are perfectly

00:34:25.310 --> 00:34:27.199
efficient at all times.

00:34:27.199 --> 00:34:30.679
How could they both win
and share the same prize?

00:34:30.679 --> 00:34:34.130
Our portfolio
resembles that win.

00:34:34.130 --> 00:34:37.670
So we say, in the strategic
portion of your portfolio,

00:34:37.670 --> 00:34:40.130
the market's going to be
right more than it's wrong.

00:34:40.130 --> 00:34:43.070
The market is
smarter than we are.

00:34:43.070 --> 00:34:45.850
Just saying the market
is mostly efficient

00:34:45.850 --> 00:34:48.850
is not the same as saying
the market's always right.

00:34:48.850 --> 00:34:50.540
But we want to do as
little as possible

00:34:50.540 --> 00:34:56.270
because, Gene Fama's math backs
up the capital asset pricing

00:34:56.270 --> 00:34:58.080
model and how the markets work.

00:34:58.080 --> 00:35:00.470
But then part of us realized
that there are bubbles

00:35:00.470 --> 00:35:03.380
and there are cycles and
there are emotional moments,

00:35:03.380 --> 00:35:05.420
and the pendulum
does swing too far.

00:35:05.420 --> 00:35:07.620
So that's why we marry
those two approaches.

00:35:07.620 --> 00:35:11.030
So seeing those two gentlemen
step up and win the Nobel Prize

00:35:11.030 --> 00:35:15.140
together perfectly aligns
with how we manage money.

00:35:15.140 --> 00:35:17.690
It's perfectly intuitive to us.

00:35:17.690 --> 00:35:21.197
So the answer to your question
is yes, you should sell.

00:35:21.197 --> 00:35:22.051
AUDIENCE: Perfect.

00:35:22.051 --> 00:35:23.030
I'm out.

00:35:23.030 --> 00:35:24.560
JOSH BROWN: The answer to your
question's, how do you know?

00:35:24.560 --> 00:35:25.520
You do not know.

00:35:25.520 --> 00:35:27.710
You will not know.

00:35:27.710 --> 00:35:29.870
But you have to
be willing to say,

00:35:29.870 --> 00:35:33.270
if I feel this way and
I'm not rules-based;

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:35.190
and it's real
estate, not stocks--

00:35:35.190 --> 00:35:37.274
there's no moving
average for a building--

00:35:37.274 --> 00:35:38.690
you have to be
willing to say, I'm

00:35:38.690 --> 00:35:42.470
willing to forgo some upside,
even if it takes three years.

00:35:42.470 --> 00:35:46.550
Because I think I would
have more regret--

00:35:46.550 --> 00:35:49.070
and remember, all of this
is regret minimisation.

00:35:49.070 --> 00:35:52.430
What would you regret more,
missing the next 20% up

00:35:52.430 --> 00:35:57.830
and cap rates keep exploding,
or seeing a 20% downdraft

00:35:57.830 --> 00:35:58.810
and having no capital?

00:35:58.810 --> 00:36:00.750
It sounds like you
already know your answer.

00:36:00.750 --> 00:36:02.360
So you should start
to sell right now.

00:36:02.360 --> 00:36:02.660
AUDIENCE: Perfect.

00:36:02.660 --> 00:36:03.880
JOSH BROWN: Like, leave
the room and just listen.

00:36:03.880 --> 00:36:04.200
AUDIENCE: I'm out.

00:36:04.200 --> 00:36:05.060
I'm leaving.

00:36:05.060 --> 00:36:06.050
JOSH BROWN: All
right, throw that box.

00:36:06.050 --> 00:36:06.530
SPEAKER: All right, who's next?

00:36:06.530 --> 00:36:07.113
Throw the box.

00:36:07.113 --> 00:36:08.810
Let's toss it back.

00:36:08.810 --> 00:36:09.680
All right.

00:36:09.680 --> 00:36:11.780
AUDIENCE: So you were
talking about the housing

00:36:11.780 --> 00:36:12.710
market earlier.

00:36:12.710 --> 00:36:17.900
And so we're kind of seeing
now the market is getting just

00:36:17.900 --> 00:36:20.720
super high-- housing,
adding the stock market,

00:36:20.720 --> 00:36:22.590
and with the recent tax cut.

00:36:22.590 --> 00:36:25.820
And I know that
the administration

00:36:25.820 --> 00:36:29.320
is pushing to roll back a
lot of the regulation that

00:36:29.320 --> 00:36:30.695
was put in place,
like Dodd-Frank

00:36:30.695 --> 00:36:31.100
and all of that kind of stuff.

00:36:31.100 --> 00:36:32.930
JOSH BROWN: Already
in progress, yeah.

00:36:32.930 --> 00:36:33.770
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:36:33.770 --> 00:36:36.230
How do you feel?

00:36:36.230 --> 00:36:37.320
What's your take on that?

00:36:37.320 --> 00:36:40.880
Do you think that the banks have
kind of learned their lesson?

00:36:40.880 --> 00:36:44.212
Or do you think that greed
will take the day again?

00:36:44.212 --> 00:36:46.670
JOSH BROWN: We'll blow up again,
but it doesn't necessarily

00:36:46.670 --> 00:36:48.830
have to be centered
around the banks.

00:36:48.830 --> 00:36:50.630
We've had plenty
of financial crises

00:36:50.630 --> 00:36:54.470
where the banks
were fringe actors.

00:36:54.470 --> 00:36:56.720
They weren't necessarily
in the center of it.

00:36:56.720 --> 00:36:58.360
If you would've told me--

00:36:58.360 --> 00:37:01.640
so September '08, Lehman
Brothers becomes the largest

00:37:01.640 --> 00:37:02.765
bankruptcy in US history.

00:37:02.765 --> 00:37:06.320
It's like $200 billion or
whatever the number is,

00:37:06.320 --> 00:37:09.875
dwarfing anything that
even comes close to that.

00:37:09.875 --> 00:37:12.680
It makes Enron look
like a walk in the park.

00:37:12.680 --> 00:37:15.170
And then a month later,
two months later,

00:37:15.170 --> 00:37:18.950
December, the Madoff
stuff starts to come out.

00:37:18.950 --> 00:37:22.250
If you had told me in
that moment, right--

00:37:22.250 --> 00:37:26.480
Bayer, AIG, Washington
Mutual, Wachovia, Merrill gets

00:37:26.480 --> 00:37:30.650
rescued, Lehman doesn't,
Madoff, $50 billion Ponzi--

00:37:30.650 --> 00:37:34.310
If you had told me
that within 10 years

00:37:34.310 --> 00:37:36.650
we would be rolling
back financial regs,

00:37:36.650 --> 00:37:39.650
I would say, no way.

00:37:39.650 --> 00:37:42.830
What could possibly
be going on that we

00:37:42.830 --> 00:37:46.280
would be anti-regulatory,
like voting in people that

00:37:46.280 --> 00:37:49.280
want less regulation, right?

00:37:49.280 --> 00:37:50.900
Well, I'll tell you
what could go on.

00:37:50.900 --> 00:37:56.870
How about a nine-year nonstop
rally in stock prices?

00:37:56.870 --> 00:38:01.190
How about the too big
to fail regulations

00:38:01.190 --> 00:38:04.010
that perversely cause
the four biggest banks

00:38:04.010 --> 00:38:06.020
to get even bigger, right?

00:38:06.020 --> 00:38:09.770
How about free money all over
the world as central banks

00:38:09.770 --> 00:38:12.350
essentially monetize debt?

00:38:12.350 --> 00:38:14.300
In Japan, they're not
just buying bonds,

00:38:14.300 --> 00:38:16.400
they're buying stock ETFs.

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:18.620
Japanese central
bank is buying REITs.

00:38:18.620 --> 00:38:19.910
Like, how about that?

00:38:19.910 --> 00:38:22.790
Maybe that could cause
the kind of environment

00:38:22.790 --> 00:38:25.490
where we're saying, we
need less regulation,

00:38:25.490 --> 00:38:26.750
because everything's fine.

00:38:26.750 --> 00:38:30.080
So the good thing about
Dodd-Frank and capital controls

00:38:30.080 --> 00:38:33.140
and Basel III-- which is like
the global agreement on how

00:38:33.140 --> 00:38:34.670
much leverage
banks should take--

00:38:34.670 --> 00:38:37.850
the good thing about
all that, perversely,

00:38:37.850 --> 00:38:39.680
is going to become a bad thing.

00:38:39.680 --> 00:38:42.590
The good thing is that banks
have never had better balance

00:38:42.590 --> 00:38:44.310
sheets, never.

00:38:44.310 --> 00:38:46.550
They have never been
in better shape.

00:38:46.550 --> 00:38:50.210
You look at leverage ratios,
you look at their ability to do

00:38:50.210 --> 00:38:53.570
pretty much anything they
want and return capital

00:38:53.570 --> 00:38:56.090
to shareholders-- big
dividends, big buybacks--

00:38:56.090 --> 00:38:57.680
never been better.

00:38:57.680 --> 00:39:00.020
So, of course, now
is a great time

00:39:00.020 --> 00:39:02.400
to loosen up the regulation.

00:39:02.400 --> 00:39:06.410
But we have not had a crisis
in 10 years, so that's why--

00:39:06.410 --> 00:39:07.694
that's the new mode.

00:39:07.694 --> 00:39:09.110
The other thing
that's happened is

00:39:09.110 --> 00:39:11.630
I think the Republicans
have done a really good job

00:39:11.630 --> 00:39:16.940
at convincing blue collar
workers that somehow removing

00:39:16.940 --> 00:39:19.730
restrictions on payday
lenders is good for them.

00:39:19.730 --> 00:39:21.770
I don't know, it's very odd.

00:39:21.770 --> 00:39:23.690
But I think what
they've been able to say

00:39:23.690 --> 00:39:28.470
to people is freedom is
being infringed upon--

00:39:28.470 --> 00:39:35.400
the freedom to drill an oil well
in your backyard, the freedom

00:39:35.400 --> 00:39:39.840
to strip mine Yellowstone
Park, our freedoms are over.

00:39:39.840 --> 00:39:40.980
And it worked.

00:39:40.980 --> 00:39:44.190
And not every regulation
is a good regulation.

00:39:44.190 --> 00:39:47.294
And Dodd-Frank is-- we
call it Frankenstein.

00:39:47.294 --> 00:39:48.960
It's not [? pretty. ?]
It's not perfect.

00:39:48.960 --> 00:39:51.630
But the fact that they've
been able to message

00:39:51.630 --> 00:39:55.050
the American public, that by
allowing those regulations

00:39:55.050 --> 00:39:59.010
it's hurting them, it resonated.

00:39:59.010 --> 00:40:00.870
So I'll see you in
the next crisis.

00:40:00.870 --> 00:40:02.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:02.760 --> 00:40:05.850
But the thing is we
would have one anyway.

00:40:05.850 --> 00:40:08.540
I can wheel off 25 crises
that have happened.

00:40:08.540 --> 00:40:11.190
It doesn't matter, high
regulation, low regulation,

00:40:11.190 --> 00:40:14.100
because risk finds a way
and everyone's memory

00:40:14.100 --> 00:40:16.746
is wiped clean
relatively quickly.

00:40:16.746 --> 00:40:19.950
So I don't think we can
regulate financial crises out

00:40:19.950 --> 00:40:22.150
of existence.

00:40:22.150 --> 00:40:24.945
SPEAKER: OK, next question.

00:40:24.945 --> 00:40:26.820
You just handed the box,
you didn't throw it.

00:40:26.820 --> 00:40:27.360
But that's OK.

00:40:27.360 --> 00:40:27.910
AUDIENCE: OK, that's fine.

00:40:27.910 --> 00:40:28.510
SPEAKER: Let's move along.

00:40:28.510 --> 00:40:29.718
AUDIENCE: I'll toss it later.

00:40:29.718 --> 00:40:31.300
Yeah, I'm interested
in your take

00:40:31.300 --> 00:40:38.950
on the companies that don't use
advice or news to make bets.

00:40:38.950 --> 00:40:42.640
They just use mathematics,
like Renaissance.

00:40:42.640 --> 00:40:44.830
And a lot of the people
who run those companies,

00:40:44.830 --> 00:40:48.130
they come from the same
places a lot of us come from--

00:40:48.130 --> 00:40:51.230
academic, mathematics,
and computer science.

00:40:51.230 --> 00:40:53.200
And as far as I
understand, they're

00:40:53.200 --> 00:40:56.050
the most successful
traders on Wall Street.

00:40:56.050 --> 00:40:58.395
JOSH BROWN: Yes, at the
current moment, absolutely.

00:40:58.395 --> 00:41:00.020
AUDIENCE: And so,
but it's interesting,

00:41:00.020 --> 00:41:03.160
because they don't care
whether Steve Jobs dies.

00:41:03.160 --> 00:41:04.744
They just trade
according to formulas.

00:41:04.744 --> 00:41:06.951
And I'm just curious about
what you think about that.

00:41:06.951 --> 00:41:09.610
JOSH BROWN: Right,
so if you walked up

00:41:09.610 --> 00:41:14.340
to an average person,
a savvy person,

00:41:14.340 --> 00:41:18.540
and you said, in 2011
I know for a fact

00:41:18.540 --> 00:41:22.190
that Steve Jobs is going
to die in 30 days--

00:41:22.190 --> 00:41:24.800
buy, sell, or hold Apple?

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:28.982
What percentage of people
would say buy Apple?

00:41:28.982 --> 00:41:29.950
AUDIENCE: A few.

00:41:29.950 --> 00:41:31.810
JOSH BROWN: 10% maybe.

00:41:31.810 --> 00:41:34.840
Everyone would say,
oh no, the magic man.

00:41:34.840 --> 00:41:37.930
And I would've said that,
because I don't know anything.

00:41:37.930 --> 00:41:40.960
Apple was worth $300
billion when Jobs died.

00:41:40.960 --> 00:41:43.060
It's worth a trillion
dollars now almost.

00:41:43.060 --> 00:41:46.840
So it's tripled under
the chief operating

00:41:46.840 --> 00:41:49.280
officer as the new CEO.

00:41:49.280 --> 00:41:51.415
He's created more value
than Steve Jobs did.

00:41:51.415 --> 00:41:54.670
It makes no sense,
completely counterintuitive.

00:41:54.670 --> 00:41:58.340
So an algorithm doesn't
care who's the CEO.

00:41:58.340 --> 00:42:01.090
Now, that's not the same
as saying that algorithms

00:42:01.090 --> 00:42:02.644
won't react to news though.

00:42:02.644 --> 00:42:04.810
So many of the trading
algorithms are-- what they're

00:42:04.810 --> 00:42:07.180
really doing is
scanning headlines

00:42:07.180 --> 00:42:11.350
and they're looking for
things like bomb, White House.

00:42:11.350 --> 00:42:16.150
And so there was a hacking
attack on the "60 Minutes"

00:42:16.150 --> 00:42:20.140
Twitter account and said a bomb
went off at the White House,

00:42:20.140 --> 00:42:24.700
and the stock market
lost like 3% in minutes.

00:42:24.700 --> 00:42:27.420
Now, that's not humans reacting.

00:42:27.420 --> 00:42:28.950
It happened too fast.

00:42:28.950 --> 00:42:31.680
So those are trading
algorithms that

00:42:31.680 --> 00:42:36.910
have specific keywords
in their instructions

00:42:36.910 --> 00:42:39.670
and they were fooled by
a hacked Twitter account.

00:42:39.670 --> 00:42:43.570
So I don't know if
machine-trading hedge

00:42:43.570 --> 00:42:47.500
funds are quite as invincible as
they might look at the moment.

00:42:50.230 --> 00:42:51.820
We're talking about
like Renaissance,

00:42:51.820 --> 00:42:53.260
which is Jim Simons.

00:42:53.260 --> 00:42:57.100
And it's an amazing story
and their returns are insane.

00:42:57.100 --> 00:42:58.780
No one even comes close.

00:42:58.780 --> 00:43:00.610
And they don't talk
to Wall Street.

00:43:00.610 --> 00:43:02.020
They don't talk to analysts.

00:43:02.020 --> 00:43:04.960
They don't attend conferences.

00:43:04.960 --> 00:43:07.540
They definitely don't
watch me on CNBC.

00:43:07.540 --> 00:43:10.720
They're PhDs running
around and codebreakers

00:43:10.720 --> 00:43:14.560
and nontraditional
financial people trying

00:43:14.560 --> 00:43:17.050
to reverse-engineer
what drives markets

00:43:17.050 --> 00:43:21.820
and figure out micro-profits
on a minute-by-minute basis.

00:43:21.820 --> 00:43:24.565
The thing with that is
that it's not novel.

00:43:27.130 --> 00:43:29.440
One of the best books ever
written about investing

00:43:29.440 --> 00:43:30.280
is "The Money Game."

00:43:30.280 --> 00:43:32.320
It was written in the 1960s.

00:43:32.320 --> 00:43:34.234
And there's a chapter
with a computer,

00:43:34.234 --> 00:43:36.025
that all the Wall Street
people are in line

00:43:36.025 --> 00:43:38.740
and they want to put
some information into it.

00:43:38.740 --> 00:43:42.950
Vonnegut wrote "Player
Piano" before the--

00:43:42.950 --> 00:43:44.086
It's not a new thing.

00:43:44.086 --> 00:43:45.460
There's just a
new version of it.

00:43:45.460 --> 00:43:47.680
And the reason why they
won't be invincible

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:50.500
is because anything
that's got success,

00:43:50.500 --> 00:43:53.350
it will attract competition.

00:43:53.350 --> 00:43:55.150
And so now what you
actually have going on

00:43:55.150 --> 00:43:58.690
is a quant arms race
amongst hedge funds.

00:43:58.690 --> 00:44:00.580
Steve Cohen is hiring quants.

00:44:00.580 --> 00:44:03.130
Paul Tudor Jones
is hiring quants.

00:44:03.130 --> 00:44:06.490
All of the big hedge funds
are loading up their firms

00:44:06.490 --> 00:44:09.220
with data scientists,
data analytics people,

00:44:09.220 --> 00:44:12.370
and they will nullify
each other's edges.

00:44:12.370 --> 00:44:16.120
Like any other business,
competition eventually arrives.

00:44:16.120 --> 00:44:18.640
So the thing with Renaissance
which has made them remarkable

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:20.290
is, they didn't
invent one algorithm

00:44:20.290 --> 00:44:21.820
and then live with it.

00:44:21.820 --> 00:44:24.580
They constantly are
coming up with new ways.

00:44:24.580 --> 00:44:26.570
That's the only answer.

00:44:26.570 --> 00:44:29.572
It's a tough, arduous process.

00:44:29.572 --> 00:44:31.030
Most people won't
be able to do it.

00:44:31.030 --> 00:44:33.610
And by the way, if you
wanted to give them money,

00:44:33.610 --> 00:44:34.600
there's no 800 number.

00:44:34.600 --> 00:44:36.280
They don't want your money.

00:44:36.280 --> 00:44:38.980
And so they're an
amazing success story.

00:44:38.980 --> 00:44:41.200
There aren't that
many other companies

00:44:41.200 --> 00:44:43.589
that will come along and
be able to replicate that.

00:44:43.589 --> 00:44:45.880
SPEAKER: Speaking of the
algorithms real quick, in case

00:44:45.880 --> 00:44:46.921
there's another question.

